            <fr:addr type="user">SP-0008</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>SP-0008.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Strong Markov property of Brownian Motion">Strong Markov property of Brownian Motion</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>27</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ (B_{t} )_{t\geq  0} ]]></fr:tex>  be a <fr:link type="local" href="SP-0001.xml" addr="SP-0001" title="Brownian motion">Brownian Motion</fr:link>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ T ]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link type="local" href="SP-000E.xml" addr="SP-000E" title="Stopping time">stopping time</fr:link>. Then, conditional on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ T < +\infty  ]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ \left ( B_{t+T} -B_{t}  \right )_{t\geq  0}  ]]></fr:tex> is another Brownian motion, independent of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ (B_{r})_{ r \leq  T } ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>N.B.</fr:strong> For the special case of deterministic times <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ T=s ]]></fr:tex>, we can prove this theorem using the definition</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>379</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">SP-0002</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>SP-0002.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Almost surely">Almost surely</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>"Almost surely" (often abbreviated a.s.) is a precise mathematical term in probability theory. It means that an event happens with probability 1.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Imagine you pick a random real number between 0 and 1. What's the probability that you pick exactly 0.5? It's 0. There are infinitely many numbers between 0 and 1, so the probability of picking any single specific number is zero. However, picking any number in that interval is certain (probability 1).</fr:p>
            <fr:p>"Almost surely" captures this distinction:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>An event occurs almost surely if the set of outcomes where the event does not occur has probability zero.</fr:li>
  <fr:li>It acknowledges that there might be some "exceptional" outcomes where the event doesn't happen, but these exceptions are so rare that their total probability is zero.</fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>In the context of <fr:link type="local" href="SP-0001.xml" addr="SP-0001" title="Brownian motion">Brownian motion</fr:link>, when we say "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B_0 = 0]]></fr:tex> almost surely", it means that 
  while theoretically it's possible for a sample path to start at, say, 0.0000001 (because the process is continuous and random), 
  the probability of that happening is zero. 
  For all practical purposes and in almost every single realization of a Brownian motion path, it will start exactly at 0.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
